2026-05-05 | Sum of Waviness in a Range

	Question
Return the sum of waviness of all numbers in the range.
	Key Insight
Checking every number individually is impossible for large ranges.
A digit can be classified as peak/valley only when:
		left digit
		current digit
		right digit
are all known.
So while constructing a number digit-by-digit,
we keep track of:
		previous digit
		second previous digit
When a new digit arrives, we can determine
whether the middle digit became a peak or valley.
This is a classic Digit DP problem.
	Approach
1.	Create function:
		F(x)
		= total waviness of all numbers
		  from 0 to x.
2.	Digit DP state:
		position
		tight
		started
		last digit
		second last digit
3.	Whenever we place a new digit d:
		a b d
		check whether b is:
				peak
				or
				valley
4.	Store:
		count of numbers
		total waviness
	for every state.
5.	Final answer:
		F(num2) - F(num1 - 1)
	Time Complexity
	O(positions × states × 10)
	Approximately O(20 × 11 × 11 × 10)
	Space Complexity
	O(states)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    struct Node {
        long long cnt;
        long long sum;
    };
    string num;
    Node dp[20][11][11][2][2];
    bool vis[20][11][11][2][2];
    Node solve(int pos,
               int prev1,
               int prev2,
               int started,
               int tight) {
        if(pos == num.size())
            return {1, 0};
        if(!tight &&
           vis[pos][prev1][prev2][started][0]) {
            return dp[pos][prev1][prev2][started][0];
        }
        int limit = tight ? num[pos] - '0' : 9;
        Node res = {0, 0};
        for(int d = 0; d <= limit; d++) {
            int ntight =
                tight && (d == limit);
            if(!started && d == 0) {
                Node nxt =
                    solve(pos + 1,
                          10,
                          10,
                          0,
                          ntight);
                res.cnt += nxt.cnt;
                res.sum += nxt.sum;
            }
            else {
                int add = 0;
                if(prev1 != 10 &&
                   prev2 != 10) {
                    if((prev1 > prev2 && prev1 > d) ||
                       (prev1 < prev2 && prev1 < d))
                        add = 1;
                }
                int newPrev2 =
                    (prev1 == 10 ? d : prev1);
                Node nxt =
                    solve(pos + 1,
                          d,
                          newPrev2,
                          1,
                          ntight);
                res.cnt += nxt.cnt;
                res.sum += nxt.sum +
                           1LL * add * nxt.cnt;
            }
        }
        if(!tight) {
            vis[pos][prev1][prev2][started][0] = true;
            dp[pos][prev1][prev2][started][0] = res;
        }
        return res;
    }
    long long get(long long x) {
        if(x < 0)
            return 0;
        memset(vis, 0, sizeof(vis));
        num = to_string(x);
        return solve(0, 10, 10, 0, 1).sum;
    }
    long long totalWaviness(long long num1,
                            long long num2) {
        return get(num2) - get(num1 - 1);
    }
};
	Key Insight
A digit's peak/valley status becomes known only after both neighbors are available. Therefore, during digit DP we remember the previous two digits. Whenever a new digit is placed, the middle digit can be evaluated immediately, allowing us to accumulate total waviness over an entire range without enumerating every number.
